    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-20T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-20T18:00:00-05:00" n="908"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d908">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/8900</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Persia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJL1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-20T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 20, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your telegrams February 18, 3 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d908fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> and 9 p.m., surprising in view of your recent report that
                    there was no important news in Persia. The Department must have an immediate and
                    complete report on Turkish and German propaganda in Persia. By what means is it
                    being carried on, what success is it making, and how can it be guarded against?
                    Is present Persian Government pro-Ally, pro-German, or truly neutral in its
                    sympathies? Is Persia seeking the withdrawal of English troops from Persia in
                    good faith or for the purpose of aiding Germany and Turkey as soon as this is
                    done? What does Persia really want and expect America to do? Investigate these
                    matters very discreetly, but also very thoroughly, and reply.</p>
                <p>The situation in Persia may become a matter of vital importance. It is essential
                    that you realize its importance and keep the Department fully informed of actual
                    situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
